    "body": "### Problem\n\nCalling `vim.fn.wildtrigger()` manually can leave pmenu drawn (although completion has ended) without a way to hide it.\nIn Vim forcing redraw hides drawn pmenu as well.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Create the following 'init.vim':\n\n    ```vim\n    set nocompatible\n    set wildmode=noselect:lastused,full\n    set wildoptions=pum\n\n    cnoremap <M-w> <Cmd>call wildtrigger()<CR>\n    cnoremap <M-r> <Cmd>redraw<CR>\n    ```\n\n2. `nvim --clean -u init.vim`\n3. Type `:s<M-w>`. Full pmenu is shown.\n4. Press `o`. Outdated pmenu is still shown, although completion has ended. This seems to be by design.\n5. Press `<M-r>`. Pmenu is still shown, although in Vim it is hidden.\n\nThis can also be reproduced not after immediately opened Neovim (with welcome text).\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nExecuting `:redraw` hides the outdated pmenu triggered by `vim.fn.wildtrigger()`. Otherwise there is no way to make sure that outdated pmenu is hidden.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.12.0-dev-1742+gad438b6b14\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo, it behaves differently and more useful\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nEndeavourOS Linux x86_64, 6.17.9-arch1-1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty 1.2.3-arch2\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nAppimage",
